  "prompt": "What is the stall speed and AOA of an f-14 with wings fully swept back?",
  "response": "The stall speed and angle of attack (AOA) for an F-14 Tomcat with its wings fully swept back can vary based on several factors including the aircraft's weight, configuration, and flight conditions. Generally, when the wings are fully swept back, the aircraft is configured for high-speed flight, and its aerodynamic characteristics change significantly.\n\nFor an F-14 with wings fully swept back (around 68 degrees):\n- The stall speed is significantly higher than with wings in the forward position due to the reduced lift generated by the wing design in the swept position. While the exact stall speed can vary, it's generally in the range of approximately 160 knots or more.\n- The angle of attack (AOA) at which the aircraft stalls also changes; typically, it would be lower than in a forward-wing position due to the aerodynamic properties of the swept wing.\n\nIt's important to note that detailed performance parameters for specific maneuvers and configurations are part of the aircraft's operational and pilot manuals, which provide comprehensive data for various conditions. For precise numbers, consulting the F-14's NATOPS (Naval Air Training and Operating Procedures Standardization) manual would be necessary.",
